  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Responding to Zhao the Commander's Rhymes at Chenfeng County
  author: Fang Shu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    High, high rises the stone plank road—I slacken rein and drift along.
    Where stream and ridge cease, ancient walls remain.
    Through mulberry groves, mist coils thick around snail-shell hovels small,
    While bird-paths crisscross where the treetops touch the lowering sky.
    The gorge brimmed full with clouds and haze transforms to painted scroll,
    One corner blessed by wind and moon awakens poet's heart.
    These days I linger in this lonely hall,
    And mountain light and water's gleam seep clean into my dreams.
  footnotes:
    - The poem is written in response to (次韻) another poem by Zhao, a military commander, following the same rhyme scheme as the original work.
    - Stone plank roads (棧) were ancient pathways carved into cliff faces, particularly common in mountainous regions of China.
    - The imagery of ruins and natural scenery suggests the speaker's meditation on transience and the passage of time.
